http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/descript.@value:
A Parcel is a way of defining some area in an urban system.
A Parcel has a Location.
A Parcel may be classified as having some type of Land Use.
There may be other types (subclasses) of Parcel, defined in more precise or different ways, such as a Zone.

The iCity-LandUse Ontology captures concepts related to land use and cover over time. The ontology reuses and extends the Land Based Classification Standards (LBCS) Ontology  presented by (Montenegro, Gomes, Urbano, and Duarte, 2011) for this purpose.

Changes from prior version:
- revised foundational ontologies
- added CLUMP and AAFC land use classifications
- imported GCI-Foundation ontology to capture population information

'A' Cropland - Land used for annual field crops such as grain, oilseeds, sugar beets, tobacco, potatoes, field vegetables and canning crops. Associated fallow, and land being cleared for field crops are also included.
'Z' Additional code added during data integration for water areas based on the CLI shoreline maps.

Treed areas >1 ha in size
Wetland with forest cover
Natural grass and shrubs used for cattle grazing
Natural grass and shrubs with no apparent use (forest openings, alpine meadows, tundra, etc.)

'H' Horticulture, poultry and fur operations. Land used for intensive cultivation of vegetables and small fruits, includes market gardens, nurseries, flower and bulb farms and sod farms. Large scale commercial fur and poultry farms are also included because of their specialized agricultural nature.

http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/descript.@value: P - Improved pasture and forage crops

http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#com.@value: 'P' Improved pasture and forage crops.- Land used for improved pasture or for the production of hay and other cultivated fodder crops, including land being cleared for these purposes.

The LBCS recognizes different dimensions of Land Use: Activity, Function, Structure, Site, and Ownership Classifications. Each dimension is further defined by a taxonomy of specialized classifications. For each dimension, we introduce an equivalent class name for disambiguation, e.g. to distinguish between the Activity dimension of land use (we refer to this as ActivityClassification) and the notion of an Activity in icity.

Land Use Classifications provide a means of describing the land cover/use in a standard way. Various classification systems are used to identify types of land use. Currently, we include LBCS, CLUMP, and AAFC.

http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/descript.@value: E - Mines, quarries, sand and gravel pits

http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#com.@value: 'E' Mines, quarries, sand and gravel pits, open excavations. Land used in the past or present for the extraction of earth materials.
'U' Non-productive woodland. Land covered by scrub growth.
'G' Orchards and vineyards. Land used for the production of tree fruits, hops and grapes.
Rock, beaches, ice, barren land
'O' Outdoor recreation - Land used for private or public outdoor recreational purposes. Some examples are: golf courses, parks, beaches, summer cottage areas, game preserves and historic sites.

http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#com.@value: 'T' Productive woodland.Wooded land with trees having over 25% canopy cover and being over 20 feet in height approximately. Artificially restocked areas, or plantations are included regardless of age. Much cut-over and burned-over land is included.

'M' Swamp, marsh, or bog. Open wetlands except those which frequently dry up or show evidence of grazing or hay cutting.
Wetland with tree cover

http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/descript.@value: K - Unimproved pasture and range land

http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#com.@value: 'K' Rough grazing and range land. Areas of natural grasslands, sedges, herbaceous plants and abandoned farmland whether used for grazing or not. Bushes and trees may cover up to 25% of the area. Intermittently wet hay lands (sloughs or meadows) are included as long as the land is utilized. Within some grassy, open woodlands, bushes and trees may exceed 25% cover if the area is actively grazed and no other use dominates.
'L' Rock and other unvegetated surfaces - rock barrens, badlands, alkaline flats, gravel bars, eroded river banks, mine dumps. Unproductive land which does not support vegetation.
'S' Sand, sand bars, sand flats, dunes and beaches - Unproductive unconsolidated land which does not support vegetation.

'B' Built-up area. Land occupied by cities, towns, and villages, or by isolated units away from settlements such as manufacturing plants, rail yards, and military camps. Parks and other open spaces within built-up areas are also included.
Undifferentiated wetland
Wetland with grass cover
